	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> <date>July 21st Ab 3rd 5601</date></p>
				<p>Dear Uncle.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The week after I left <placeName>Baltimore</placeName> I wrote a few times to<lb/> <persName>David Judah</persName> upon some little affairs he had entrusted to me&#44; I<lb/> desired to be remembered. Since then I have been kept pretty<lb/> much engaged in various ways&#59; first&#44;  old <persName>Mrs. Levy</persName> died&#44; &#40;<persName>Aaron&#39;s</persName> wife&#41;<lb/> and had to attend prayers morning and evening at more than<lb/> a mile distance from my place&#59; and next we had lately a meeting<lb/> to propose a plan for a general union of all the Jews in <placeName>America</placeName><lb/> under one general church government at the head of which are<lb/> to be placed three learned men. I was put upon the committee<lb/> to mature<add>&#63;</add> the plan&#44; and <del>accordingly</del> was delegated by them<lb/> afterward  to draw up rules &#38; regulations. I had to go to work<lb/> accordingly and did what had been asked of me&#59; and the committee had<lb/> thereupon several meetings to debate after and amend my rough<lb/> draft. In the main it was adopted&#44; and it was updated last<lb/> <date>Sunday</date> to a general meeting&#44; and adopted and ordained to be printed<lb/> for general circulation&#44; and  as soon as it is ready I will send<lb/> it on&#44; and I hope that you will at least approve of the outline<lb/> if even all the details do not meet your views. At the first<lb/> meeting &#40;the <date>Sunday</date> after I left you&#41; I made an extemporaneous address<lb/> of near an hour long to introduce the measure to public notice&#59;<lb/> altho&#39; not prepared with even a single note&#44; people were pleased to<lb/> say that it was the best address they had heard from me&#59; but this is so<lb/> often  said about my works that I do not give much for such a compliment<lb/> any farther than that it proves that the people are not tired of hearing me</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
			<p rend="indent(1)">In addition to the above labour which might have been enough in<lb/> a general way&#44; I have been constantly occupied in writing letters and<lb/> editing a work for a gentleman by name of <persName>Dr. Louis Solomon</persName> a<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add> from <placeName>Metz</placeName>&#44; who is not acquainted with the English. So<lb/> you see I have not been very idle. But in truth&#44; people are afraid<lb/> of my wasting away&#44; so they keep me busy all they can.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Do let me hear soon how you are at home. Tell <persName>Rachel</persName><lb/> I sent her mother the book she gave me yesterday two weeks by<lb/> <persName>Messrs Hanford &#38;  Sale</persName><add>&#63;</add>. No doubt she has heard this before today.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I hope this day week to send you the report all printed&#44;<lb/> and therefore I do not want to fatigue you now with more<lb/> details.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Please to give my love to Aunt <persName>R.</persName> <persName>Mr. D P</persName><lb/> &#38; <persName>Rachel</persName>&#44; as also to <persName>Mrs. J.</persName> &#38; <persName>Mr. &#38; Mrs. B</persName> &#38; Family.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">With high respect I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">your</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">obt nephew</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><add>&#63;</add></p>
				<p><persName>Mr. Zalma Rehine</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>No 25 Camden St.</placeName></p>
				<p><hi rend="underline">Single</hi>. <hi rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Baltimore</placeName></hi></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Md.</p>
		</body>
